pr_body:
Solving #2.

Four models in a class:
- LSCP
- MCLP 
  - with mixin - percentage covered
- P-Median
  -  with mixin - mean distance  
- P-Center

This pull request adds these models, notebooks for each model explaining the model with lattice 10x10, and one notebook for real-world problem. The last one uses the store site dataset provided by [Huanfa's repository](https://github.com/huanfachen/Open_source_location_cover_models) used in [Open‚Äësource approaches for location cover models: capabilities and efficiency](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10109-021-00350-w) paper.

```python
import platform

operating_system = platform.platform()[:7].lower()
if operating_system == "windows":
    WINDOWS = True
else:
    WINDOWS = False
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 10, 1, 11, 30, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jGaboardi', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 686229436, 'comment_body': 'Does `distances` need to be declared here and again in line 350?

I ran all the tests without this LOC and gave me no errors.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 11, 1, 27, 45, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'gegen07', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 686832351, 'comment_body': 'Though it seems in LOC177 `service_load` is being passed into `from_cost_matrix()`, which is then used in LOC76-77 the calculate `aij` (the population weighted distance matrix). Best to remove all mention of `aij` & weights from the `PCenter` class.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 11, 13, 29, 47, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jGaboardi', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 687148279, 'comment_body': "The `MAX_COVERAGE`/`service_radius` parameters are only applicable for the MCLP and LSCP. I noticed this while reviewing the results and saw that 5/5 candidate facility sites were being selected, when it should be 4/5. * check the plot titles for the final results in cell 25 üòÖ and rerun the final ***PCenter from geodataframes*** cell.
* review the *p*-median notebook for similar inconsistencies.


Things are looking good here. These are simply minor clean up & revision activities that happen in any PR this size.

pr_body:
Solving #2.

Four models in a class:
- LSCP
- MCLP 
  - with mixin - percentage covered
- P-Median
  -  with mixin - mean distance  
- P-Center

This pull request adds these models, notebooks for each model explaining the model with lattice 10x10, and one notebook for real-world problem. The last one uses the store site dataset provided by [Huanfa's repository](https://github.com/huanfachen/Open_source_location_cover_models) used in [Open‚Äësource approaches for location cover models: capabilities and efficiency](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10109-021-00350-w) paper.

Currently, it is set as the `os` package. Are we using the `os` python package anywhere else here? If so, we can simply rename the variable like so:

```python
import platform

operating_system = platform.platform()[:7].lower()
if operating_system == "windows":
    WINDOWS = True
else:
    WINDOWS = False
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 10, 1, 11, 30, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jGaboardi', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 686229436, 'comment_body': 'Does `distances` need to be declared here and again in line 350?

See (Chapter 21):

> **Horner M.W., Widener M.J.** (2010) How do Socioeconomic Characteristics Interact with Equity and Efficiency Considerations? An Analysis of Hurricane Disaster Relief Goods Provision. In: Jiang B., Yao X. (eds) Geospatial Analysis and Modelling of Urban Structure and Dynamics. GeoJournal Library, vol 99. I think that I did not delete this LOC because in constraints I used the cost_matrix without weighting. I ran all the tests without this LOC and gave me no errors.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 11, 1, 27, 45, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'gegen07', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 686832351, 'comment_body': 'Though it seems in LOC177 `service_load` is being passed into `from_cost_matrix()`, which is then used in LOC76-77 the calculate `aij` (the population weighted distance matrix). Best to remove all mention of `aij` & weights from the `PCenter` class.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 11, 13, 29, 47, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jGaboardi', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 687148279, 'comment_body': "The `MAX_COVERAGE`/`service_radius` parameters are only applicable for the MCLP and LSCP. I noticed this while reviewing the results and saw that 5/5 candidate facility sites were being selected, when it should be 4/5. We'll need to update the code cells (23 & 26) and explanations before them.

* check the plot titles for the final results in cell 25 üòÖ and rerun the final ***PCenter from geodataframes*** cell.
* review the *p*-median notebook for similar inconsistencies.


Things are looking good here. These are simply minor clean up & revision activities that happen in any PR this size.


", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 11, 20, 9, 23, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jGaboardi', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 687843841, 'comment_body': "I can see that you changed P-Median to P-Center in cell 19, but the plots are still labeled P-Median in the output of cell 20 and 21. pr_body:
Solving #2.

Four models in a class:
- LSCP
- MCLP 
  - with mixin - percentage covered
- P-Median
  -  with mixin - mean distance  
- P-Center

This pull request adds these models, notebooks for each model explaining the model with lattice 10x10, and one notebook for real-world problem. The last one uses the store site dataset provided by [Huanfa's repository](https://github.com/huanfachen/Open_source_location_cover_models) used in [Open‚Äësource approaches for location cover models: capabilities and efficiency](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10109-021-00350-w) paper.

', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 9, 22, 6, 48, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jGaboardi', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 685620039, 'comment_body': 'You'll need to [define `os` as the string of the operating system](https://github.com/jGaboardi/tigernet/blob/be2724e662b183a3016b4bf6a0b18c34a8f51985/tigernet/tests/test_tigernet_empirical_gdf.py#L13-L16). Currently, it is set as the `os` package. Are we using the `os` python package anywhere else here? If so, we can simply rename the variable like so:

```python
import platform

operating_system = platform.platform()[:7].lower()
if operating_system == "windows":
    WINDOWS = True
else:
    WINDOWS = False
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 10, 1, 11, 30, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jGaboardi', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 686229436, 'comment_body': 'Does `distances` need to be declared here and again in line 350?

* also check this in MCLP, *p*-median, and *p*-center', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 10, 18, 39, 47, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jGaboardi', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 686408676, 'comment_body': 'The *p*-center problem is traditionally unweighted. See (Chapter 21):

> **Horner M.W., Widener M.J.** (2010) How do Socioeconomic Characteristics Interact with Equity and Efficiency Considerations? An Analysis of Hurricane Disaster Relief Goods Provision. In: Jiang B., Yao X. (eds) Geospatial Analysis and Modelling of Urban Structure and Dynamics. GeoJournal Library, vol 99. Springer, Dordrecht. https://doi.org/10.1007/978-90-481-8572-6_20', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 11, 0, 32, 41, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jGaboardi', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 686409429, 'comment_body': 'We may want to keep this in if we will be adding capacity constraints, but the weighted distance should not be used in the *p*-center problem.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 11, 0, 35, 19, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jGaboardi', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 686426329, 'comment_body': 'Hm. I think that I did not delete this LOC because in constraints I used the cost_matrix without weighting. I ran all the tests without this LOC and gave me no errors.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 11, 1, 27, 45, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'gegen07', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 686832351, 'comment_body': 'Though it seems in LOC177 `service_load` is being passed into `from_cost_matrix()`, which is then used in LOC76-77 the calculate `aij` (the population weighted distance matrix). Then `aij` is passed in to `PCenter()` in LOC 79. Since the *p*-center problem should be solved without population demand, only the unweighted distances should be used as an input. Best to remove all mention of `aij` & weights from the `PCenter` class.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 11, 13, 29, 47, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jGaboardi', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 687148279, 'comment_body': "The `MAX_COVERAGE`/`service_radius` parameters are only applicable for the MCLP and LSCP. For the *p*-median and *p*-center problems the only parameter should be your `P_FACILITIES` parameter. I noticed this while reviewing the results and saw that 5/5 candidate facility sites were being selected, when it should be 4/5. We'll need to update the code cells (23 & 26) and explanations before them.

* check the plot titles for the final results in cell 25 üòÖ and rerun the final ***PCenter from geodataframes*** cell.
* review the *p*-median notebook for similar inconsistencies.


Things are looking good here. These are simply minor clean up & revision activities that happen in any PR this size.


", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 11, 20, 9, 23, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jGaboardi', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 687843841, 'comment_body': "I can see that you changed P-Median to P-Center in cell 19, but the plots are still labeled P-Median in the output of cell 20 and 21. Maybe let's try to rerun again to fix this?

Also, go ahead and fully rerun `facloc-real-world.ipynb` (the *p*-median plots seem to have not been run). And üëç üëç for the solver comparison at the end of `facloc-real-world.ipynb`. Very interesting stuff. I'm wondering if maybe we should include solve time in the print out for comparison. Maybe I'll include that later.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 12, 15, 29, 28, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jGaboardi', 'type': 'User'}]
